# Catalyst One — Data Integrity & Analytics Standard v1.0

**Status:** FOUNDATION STANDARD  
**This is a permanent architectural standard.**

It applies to every dashboard, chart, report, score, metric, AI recommendation, and operational insight throughout Catalyst One.

---

## Objective

Catalyst One is an **Enterprise Decision Support System**.

Management will rely on the platform for operational, financial, and strategic decisions.

Therefore:

- Every number displayed must represent **actual business data**
- No visualisation should exist purely for demonstration

---

## Source of Truth

Every report, dashboard, KPI, chart, score, and counter must derive its values from the **enterprise data model**.

- No independent calculations disconnected from SSOT
- No duplicate business logic
- No disconnected datasets

Prefer shared derive / engine modules over per-screen ad-hoc math.

---

## Real-Time Principle

All operational dashboards must reflect the **current business state**.

When business data changes, affected metrics must **automatically refresh**.

Examples:

- Stage / sub-stage changes
- Opportunity creation / closure
- Disbursal
- Customer updates
- Task / follow-up completion
- Assignment changes

**Implementation expectation:** subscribe to the module’s SSOT update channel (e.g. `subscribeLoanFilesUpdated` / equivalent), not only initial mount or cross-tab `storage` alone. Polling is a fallback, not a substitute for same-session refresh.

---

## No Mock Business Data

- Mock or seeded data may only be used during **development**
- Production dashboards must **never** display demo values as if they were live business results
- Users must never make decisions using artificial data

When seed data is unavoidable for empty environments, label it clearly as demo / seed — never present it as production truth.

---

## Every Calculation Requires Business Logic

Every displayed metric must have a **documented calculation**.

Examples:

- Operational Health Score
- Financial Health Score
- Radar Direction / Operational Vector
- Risk Score
- Conversion Ratio
- Pipeline Velocity
- Average Processing Time
- Productivity Score
- Revenue Forecast

Every metric must have a clearly defined formula (code comments + constants / admin config where applicable).

---

## Configurable Business Rules

Business rules must not be hardcoded where practical.

Calculations should be configurable through the **Administration Console** so authorised administrators can refine logic without application code changes.

Examples:

- Risk / Health Score weightages
- Priority rules
- SLA thresholds
- Escalation rules
- Performance scoring
- Eligibility thresholds

---

## Explainability

Every metric should be explainable.

Where appropriate, users should understand:

- How was this calculated?
- Which records contributed?
- Which business rules were applied?
- Why did this score change?

No black-box calculations for decision-critical metrics.

---

## Auditability

Business calculations should be traceable.

Changes to configurable rules should be auditable, recording at minimum:

- Who changed the rule
- When it changed
- Previous value
- New value

---

## Consistency

- The same metric must always produce the same result from the same data
- Business logic must exist **only once**
- Avoid duplicate implementations across screens

**Canonical rule:** see `enterprise-metric-single-implementation.mdc` — every enterprise metric has exactly one shared calculation; screens, reports, dashboards, APIs, and AI modules must consume it. No formula duplication.

---

## Decision First

Every chart should answer a **business question**.

If a chart does not help users make a better decision, it should not exist.

---

## Final Principle

Catalyst One is not a reporting system.

It is an **Enterprise Decision Intelligence Platform**.

Every visualisation must be:

- Accurate
- Traceable
- Explainable
- Based on real business data

Business decisions should be made with complete confidence in the information presented.

---

## Definition of Done (analytics surfaces)

Before marking a dashboard / metric / insight complete:

- [ ] Values derive from enterprise SSOT
- [ ] Same-session data changes refresh the view
- [ ] Formula documented (no opaque magic numbers without rationale)
- [ ] No production demo-as-truth presentation
- [ ] Logic not duplicated elsewhere (or consolidated) — see Single Implementation Standard
- [ ] Explainability path considered for decision-critical scores
- [ ] Configurable / auditable path noted when admin rules apply

If any required item fails for a production surface, it is **not** production-ready.

---

## Relationship to other rules

- Complements `enterprise-metric-single-implementation.mdc` (exactly one formula per metric)
- Complements `enterprise-screen-ux-standard.mdc` (layout / usability)
- Complements `enterprise-workspace-ux.mdc` (workspace chrome)
- Complements `chanakya-radar.mdc` and module-specific derive engines
- When UX and data integrity conflict on what to show, **never sacrifice accuracy for decoration**
